A " golden budget rule in the constitution
In Austria's government in power of the great socialist/Christian Democrat coalition has decided on Tuesday to include a " golden budget rule in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and avoid a possible degradation by credit rating agencies in the top-rated Austria (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Mr Faymann, personally, is the decision of the exit door of the Council of Ministers, although the public Austrian state debt 74.6%, far above the set by the Maastricht Treaty criterion of 60%, but well below the debt levels of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"The solvency of Austria not fallen at a stroke from AAA to AA +, we would have three billion euros each year to pay interest rates," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister.
Austria is also a demand of the Brussels summit of countries in the euro zone on 26 October: the heads of state and government had demanded the inclusion of reducing public deficits by the end of 2012, and a return to the public accounts of the same weight in the Constitution or by adopting a similar law.
The action taken by the Austrian government similar to the "German model" because Germany was the first European country to such a "rule" was included in the Constitution.
By the year 2017 should reduce the structural budget deficit every year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP), from 2017 should not exceed the structural budget deficit, the state's 0.35% of GDP, whereas the regional states, as well as the communities should have balanced budgets.
The aim is to eradicate the budget debt under the Maastricht agreement established 60% criterion in the horizon of 2020/21.
